item.title: Big question
item.dc:creator: @exps35 exps35
item.description:
@exps35 wrote:

[quote=“magma, post:1, topic:246592”][quote author=exps35 link=topic=322938.msg2551555#msg2551555 date=1227583017]
They cannot base any judgements or punishments towards you from something you do from the privacy of your own home.
[/quote]Dead wrong, adults seem to see this logic in a completely different way than we do. I’ve been ‘punished’ at school loads of times for stuff I’ve done at home that is perfectly legal and has no direct link with school, but they just do - ethics etc.

Also, if you apply for a good school or something they usually search for myspace/facebook pages and basically don’t let you in if you have anything ‘wrong’ on there. Often the same with jobs and other important stuff.[/quote]

In America, it’s a violation of your rights.

I’m technically wrong when I said they can’t base judgments, because they most likely will.
However, they have no jurisdiction to instigate in your personal life and/or freedoms.

Yes, you wont be hired if a employer sees photos of you doing illicit drugs on your myspace (which is just stupid on your part), however, they cannot fire you for just disagreeing with the way you talk over the internet.

One of America’s better ideas imo.

Read full topic
